  "prompt": "What is the latent heat of a fusion?",
  "response": "The latent heat of fusion is the amount of heat required to change a substance from a solid to a liquid at its melting point, with no change in temperature.\n\nHere's a breakdown:\n\n*   **Latent Heat:**  \"Latent\" means hidden. This heat is absorbed or released without changing the temperature of the substance.  It's used to break or form intermolecular bonds.\n\n*   **Fusion:**  This refers to the phase transition from solid to liquid, also known as melting.\n\n*   **Definition:**  The latent heat of fusion is the energy per unit mass (or per mole) needed to completely melt the solid at its melting temperature.\n\n*   **Units:** Common units are:\n    *   Joule per kilogram (J/kg) or kilojoule per kilogram (kJ/kg)\n    *   Calorie per gram (cal/g) or kilocalorie per kilogram (kcal/kg)\n    *   British thermal unit per pound (BTU/lb)\n\n*   **Important Considerations:**\n    *   The process is reversible. The same amount of heat is *released* when the liquid freezes back into a solid at its freezing point (which is the same temperature as the melting point).  This heat released during freezing is sometimes called the latent heat of solidification.\n    *   The temperature remains constant *during* the phase change. All the energy goes into breaking the bonds holding the solid together.\n    *   Different substances have different latent heats of fusion due to differences in their molecular structure and the strength of intermolecular forces.\n\n**Formula:**\n\nThe heat (Q) required to melt a mass (m) of a substance is given by:\n\n```\nQ = m * Lf\n```\n\nWhere:\n\n*   Q = Heat energy (Joules, calories, etc.)\n*   m = Mass of the substance (kg, g, etc.)\n*   Lf = Latent heat of fusion (J/kg, cal/g, etc.)\n\n**Example:**\n\nThe latent heat of fusion of water is approximately 334 kJ/kg (or 80 cal/g). This means that it takes 334,000 Joules of energy to melt 1 kilogram of ice at 0\u00b0C into water at 0\u00b0C. Conversely, when 1 kilogram of water at 0\u00b0C freezes into ice at 0\u00b0C, it releases 334,000 Joules of energy.\n",
